{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The evaluate-stage command stores grounding into a dedicated `grounding` artifact, not the `plan` artifact.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Pairwise tournament: Integration beats Unit because the failure boundary is the handoff between evaluate-stage orchestration and artifact persistence (wrong slot write), not just one pure function. Integration beats System because this can be reproduced with in-process modules and a local artifact store; no real OS/network/subprocess is required. Rejection gate: Agentic rejected because behavior text is about destination artifact key (`grounding` vs `plan`), not model output quality; Workflow rejected because only one stage write behavior is under test.","test_description":"Run evaluate-stage with a deterministic stubbed model response and a real in-process artifact repository. Assert exactly one new/updated `grounding` artifact is written and `plan` is unchanged by this stage. This catches real module-wiring regressions in command->artifact-store mapping.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The implement-stage flow reads grounding when available and still writes its execution output to `plan`.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Pairwise tournament: Integration beats Unit because correctness depends on interaction between artifact read path (`grounding`) and write path (`plan`) across modules. Integration beats System because no real OS/network/subprocess behavior is required to surface wrong artifact routing. Rejection gate: Agentic rejected because behavior text focuses on read/write plumbing and output destination, not semantic quality of LLM output; Workflow rejected because this behavior can be isolated to implement-stage flow with pre-seeded artifacts.","test_description":"Seed run context with a `grounding` artifact, execute implement flow with deterministic generation stub, and assert implement consumed grounding input path while persisting final output only to `plan`. Also assert existing `grounding` remains intact. This catches read/write cross-module regressions.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.06,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Deep-dive no longer overwrites `plan` as a redundant side effect when diagnosis already exists in issue content.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Pairwise tournament: Integration beats Unit because failure appears at boundary between issue-content diagnosis detection and artifact-write side effects. Integration beats System because the side-effect bug is reproducible entirely in-process. Rejection gate: Agentic rejected because disqualifying text is 'diagnosis already exists in issue content' and expected result is suppression of a write side effect, not validating model judgment quality; Workflow rejected because this is a single-stage side-effect guard.","test_description":"Provide issue content that already includes diagnosis, run deep-dive stage with deterministic internals, and assert no write occurs to `plan` (or no mutation if it already exists). Verify other expected deep-dive outputs still occur. This catches real orchestration side-effect regressions.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.55,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Artifact lineage is preserved so implement can read the `grounding` artifact produced earlier in the same run context.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Pairwise tournament: Integration beats Unit because lineage bugs occur in cross-module state handoff (producer stage -> run context store -> consumer stage). Integration beats System because behavior text scopes this to 'same run context' and does not require real OS/process/network boundaries. Rejection gate: Agentic rejected because lineage preservation is state plumbing; model quality is not the assertion target. Workflow rejected because this can be tested with staged calls in one in-process harness without requiring full agentic chain semantics.","test_description":"In one run-context fixture, invoke grounding-producing stage to persist `grounding`, then invoke implement-stage reader. Assert implement resolves the exact prior artifact instance/version from lineage metadata and does not read stale/global state. This catches real context-propagation failures.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"In a full multi-step agent run (`deep-dive -> write-plan/evaluate -> implement`), the final implementation plan reflects grounding produced earlier in the run.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"Pairwise tournament: Integration beats Unit because failure depends on staged handoff across multiple components, not a single function. System is not the deciding boundary since real OS/network is not the key risk here. LLM-DEP + MULTI-STEP upgrade: this behavior explicitly requires a full multi-step agent run and correctness depends on downstream model behavior reflecting earlier grounding, so multiple agentic decisions are sequenced. Rejection gate: Agentic (single-step) rejected because behavior text explicitly requires chain `deep-dive -> write-plan/evaluate -> implement`, i.e., multi-step agent pipeline.","test_description":"Execute an end-to-end run with real model calls across all three stages using a uniquely identifiable grounding fact generated/confirmed in evaluate. Assert final implement plan substantively incorporates that grounding fact (not just artifact existence). Repeat enough runs with acceptance criteria tolerant to variance to catch real non-deterministic handoff/usage failures.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0.55}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"When grounding is absent, implement falls back safely and still emits a valid plan artifact without corrupting other stored artifacts.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Pairwise tournament: Integration beats Unit because this validates fallback orchestration plus artifact-store side effects across modules (absence handling + safe writes). Integration beats System because no real OS/network/subprocess dependency is needed to reproduce missing-grounding fallback bugs. Rejection gate: Agentic rejected because behavior text targets fallback control flow and artifact integrity, not model output quality; Workflow rejected because this is implement-stage behavior under one missing-input condition, not a multi-agent pipeline assertion.","test_description":"Run implement in a context with no `grounding` artifact but with other pre-existing artifacts. Assert a syntactically valid `plan` artifact is produced via fallback path, no unrelated artifacts are modified/deleted, and storage invariants hold. This catches real corruption/regression at module boundaries.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.02}}]}
